Spring.description: From columns of gentle bubbles to gushing flows forced by raw power, why not experience diving in a natural spring and tick it off your bucket list?

River.description: Inland river diving delivers incredible scenery unique to the locale; there are thousands of rivers across the globe offering very different experiences.

Ocean.description: The largest bodies of water on the planet have infinite gifts: from unique fish to stunning macro life and coral, you'll never get bored of this paradise.

Fjord.description: Kelp, wrecks, tiny life, warm currents, deep-water coral and lots more - fjords across the world offer unique ecosystems bracketed by high cliffs.

Channel.description: From the shipwrecks of Sussex in the UK to the rich pelagic encounters on strong Maldivian currents, you'll find incredible channel dives across the globe.

Cavern.description: The thrill of cavern diving is clear: to enter a new world and discover its secrets. Unlike cave diving, cavern diving is a form of recreational diving.

Archaelogical.description: Archeological dive sites are a unique historical lens: head back in time as you dive locations that are hundreds or even thousands of years old.

Wall.description: All your desires in one place: wall dives combine small reef fish, large pelagics, gorgeous coral at jaunty angles, plus nooks and crannies galore.

Sea Loch.description: Protected by Scotland's craggy mountains, sea lochs offer unmissable underwater reefs, clear waters and marine life including conger eel and starfish.

Sandy Bottom.description: Clams, sandy eels, sole, crocodile fish and so much more - across the globe, there's incredible life to discover if you choose to dive a sandy bottom.

Reef.description: Coral reefs are one of the ocean's dazzling gifts to divers. As we enjoy this unique terrain, we must remember our obligation to protect it.

Quarry.description: Offering inland, current-free diving with easy access, quarries often have a myriad of intriguing and submerged and sunken items to explore.

Pool.description: The perfect place to learn, pools offer calm environments to learn, refresh or advance your scuba skills - explore further, for longer, through education.

Pinnacle.description: From small mountains to ragged peaks, pinnacles are isolated formations in deep water that emerge gloriously out the blue - with unique sea life and topography.

Muck.description: The beauty's in the detail: get up close and personal with the unusual and the exotic as you explore the celebrated ecology that lies in the sediment layer.

Lake.description: Minimal currents, easy access, inland locations - lakes offer scuba divers a fresh, totally different underwater experience than the open ocean.

Drift.description: Time to go with the flow - use less energy and see more glorious coral and marine life as you drift along leisurely on the ocean current.

Beach.description: Beach dives - commonly called shore dives - offer unique topography and easy access. Set your own schedule and dive as little or as much as you want.

Cave.description: Intrigued? There's no denying the exhilaration that comes from exploring the unexplored in some of the world's most stunning flooded caves.

Wreck.description: These sunken treasures, teeming with history, offer a glimpse of times gone by: there are thousands across the world lying in silence.
